claim.claim-text:
1. A method of setting an apparent optical length of at least one optical fiber for a given optical wavelength, comprising the steps of: 
(a) trimming at least one optical fiber to an actual length approximating a desired actual length; 
(b) launching a monochromatic beam of light into one end of the at least one trimmed optical fiber and determining an arrival phase angle imparted by the at least one trimmed optical fiber to the monochromatic beam over the actual length of the at least one trimmed optical fiber; 
(c) comparing the determined arrival phase angle with a reference value representing a desired arrival phase shift angle; and 
(d) heating the at least one trimmed optical fiber selectively to vary a refractive index thereof in response to comparison of the determined arrival phase angle with the reference value to change the arrival phase angle so as to set a desired apparent length of the at least one trimmed optical fiber.

10. An apparatus for setting an apparent optical length of at least one optical fiber for a given optical wavelength, comprising: 
a light source for launching a monochromatic beam of light into an upstream end of the at least one optical fiber; 
a phase shift sensor for determining an arrival phase angle imparted by the at least one optical fiber to the monochromatic beam over the apparent optical length of the at least one optical fiber; 
a comparator comparing the determined arrival phase angle with a reference value representing a desired arrival phase angle; 
an oven receiving an optical fiber of the at least optical fiber; and 
a temperature control unit coupled to the oven for selectively varying a refractive index of the at least one optical fiber in response to comparison of the determined arrival phase angle with the reference value by selectively heating the at least one optical fiber to change the determined arrival phase angle so as to set a desired apparent optical length of the at least one fiber.
